In article <2o7id2$rk0@news.acns.nwu.edu>, Jeff Bishop <jbishop@nwu.edu> wrote:
>In article <abellCo0E3u.9CI@netcom.com>,
>Steven T. Abell <abell@netcom.com> wrote:
>>With the advent of personal computers, the Should The Government Allow Strong
>>Crypto debate becomes just like the Should The Government Allow Firearms
>>debate:
>
>You're giving him too much credit here.  Much as I abhor gun control, I
>must grant the gun-grabbers one point to which David is utterly oblivious:
>it is actually possible to kill someone with a firearm.  But with
>cryptography?!  Still, it is not particularly surprising that many of the
>people attacking one are hostile to the other as well.

This is an argument with blinders on. Consider how many lives could have
been saved at Pearl Harbor if the traffic from Japan had been decrypted more
rapidly. Consider the terrorist plots thwarted. Consider the insights into,
say, Saddam's war plans.

Lives can and have been lost by the inability to read the bad guys' crypto.


David


